<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Museveni on Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Museveni on Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2805193194 Vienna WIENER ZEITUNG in German 28 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2805193194 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna WIENER ZEITUNG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Museveni Meets With Klestil"] </F>
  [Text] Vienna -- The UN Human Rights Commission's 
resolution condemning the genocide in Rwanda offers a 
possibility to bring about a cease-fire between the warring 
parties, Ugandan President Yoweri Kaguta Museveni said in Vienna. 
  After his meeting with Federal President Thomas Klestil in 
Vienna Museveni said that efforts are being undertaken to bring 
about a cease-fire on the basis of that resolution. There will 
be an international trial calling the perpetrators to account, 
"because there can be no peace without justice," Museveni said. 
  Commenting on the Austro-Ugandan framework agreement on 
development cooperation that was signed on Thursday [26 May], 
Museveni said that real development results from investment, not 
from financial assistance. Investment is based on reciprocity; 
with neither party "a parasite living off the other." Talks 
with Austrian businesspeople have been very satisfactory, 
Museveni said. 
  Klestil told the press that the framework agreement will 
increase opportunities for cooperation. 
  Uganda is a country full of natural beauty and has been 
economically and politically stable over the past few years. 
With these words at the Austrian Economic Chamber on Friday, 
Museveni tried to establish contacts with the Austrian tourist 
industry and potential investors and trading partners. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-42187 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu104_a_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rejects Military Intervention </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rejects Military Intervention </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2705142594 Vienna DER STANDARD in German 27 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU2705142594 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DER STANDARD </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Vienna -- The international community should 
confine itself to "purely humanitarian actions" in Rwanda, 
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni says: "One should not try to 
govern countries. This mistake was made in Somalia." Therefore, 
he is against a military intervention. 
  "If I take food from point A to point B and I am stopped by 
a 
gang, I can shoot them. If I evacuate civilians and someone 
wants to kill them, I can defend them. But this is different 
from the attempt to disarm the Somalis," Museveni said at a 
joint news conference with Chancellor Vranitzky in Vienna on 
Thursday [26 May]. 
  The Rwandan rebels are not supported by Uganda, he said. In 
answer to the question of where the rebels get arms from, he 
answered: "When we were fighting, we did not have a special 
country from which we got weapons. We either bought them on the 
black market or took them off our opponents." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

