<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Firm Suspected of Money Laundering </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Firm Suspected of Money Laundering </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0106104194 Munich FOCUS in German 30 May 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> AU0106104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich FOCUS </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Subsidies for Eastern Mafia?"] </F>
  [Text] Ten fish trawlers are irritating Bonn. They are to 
be built by the Peene shipyard in Wolgast for the Russian Ohodsk 
Fishing Company, which moved to the tax paradise of Limassol, 
Cyprus. Bonn wants to subsidize the order volume of 200 million 
German marks [DM] with DM11.85 million. Mecklenburg-Western 
Pomerania is to contribute the same amount; negotiations are 
currently going on. The deal would secure 500 shipyard jobs for 
about two years. 
  However, "in this way we are financing Russian tax 
refugees," 
a confidant of Economics Minister Rexrodt (Free Democratic Party 
of Germany) stated critically. Officials in the ministry are 
currently examining whether money from the Russian mafia is 
being laundered in the deal. The fishing company, which already 
has 26 fishing ships, belongs to Russians who apparently want to 
circumvent the high taxes in their homeland. 
  Johannes Ludewig, head of the Department for Economics and 
Finances in the Chancellor's Office, arranged the deal during 
Russian President Yeltsin's visit to Kohl. Nobody knows why 
Yeltsin supported the Ohodsk group so much. However, there is 
another snag to the deal: Schwerin wants to wait for Brussels' 
agreement to the contract before it forks out subsidies -- and 
it is not certain because the amount of the subsidies exceeds 
the permitted European Union framework of 9 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

