<H3> <TI>   Mitterrand: Franco-German Axis Unchanged </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mitterrand: Franco-German Axis Unchanged </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR3105154694 Paris LE MONDE in French 31 May 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> BR3105154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE MONDE </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Bonn and Paris Step Up Cooperation"] </F>
  [Text] Chancellor Helmut Kohl and President Francois 
Mitterrand were due to meet in Mulhouse on Monday 30 and Tuesday 
31 May for the 63d Franco-German summit. This meeting will make 
it possible to prepare for the European Council meeting in Corfu 
on 24 and 25 June, the G-7 summit in Naples on 8 and 9 July, and 
the German and French terms as president of the European Union 
[EU] which will take place in succession from 1 July. Elysee 
[office of the French president] spokesman Jean Musitelli 
confirmed the creation of "a high-level working group which 
would have the task...of ensuring full consultation between our 
two countries." 
  German Government spokesman Dieter Vogel also confirmed that 
Paris and Bonn planned to combine their efforts to make their 
respective presidencies of the EU a success for Europe. "We may 
assume that the major squalls are behind us," Mr. Musitelli 
stressed, referring to the crisis in the European Monetary 
System, the GATT negotiations, and to the "uncertainties linked 
with the ratification of the Maastricht Treaty and the problems 
of expansion to include four new members." 
  In addition, in an interview published by L'ALSACE and the 
BADISCHES ZEITUNG, Francois Mitterrand explained that he did not 
see "why and how Europe's `center of gravity' should shift 
following the expansion" of the EU: "Look at a map of Europe: 
Germany and France have never been more `central' in every sense 
of the term." 

</TEXT>

