<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mikhailidhis Returns From Paris, To Go to Athens </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mikhailidhis Returns From Paris, To Go to Athens </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2805050594 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2805050594 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The foreign ministers of Cyprus and Greece, Alekos 
Mikhailidhis and Karolos Papoulias, will meet tomorrow in Athens 
to decide on the handling of the Cyprus issue in the near 
future. This was stated by Foreign Minister Mikhailidhis at 
Larnaca Airport upon his return from Paris, where he 
participated in the conference for stability in Europe. 
Mikhailidhis added that tomorrow's meeting with the Greek 
foreign minister is considered necessary due to the developments 
in the Cyprus issue. During the meeting, he said, we will 
exchange views and information and discuss the National 
Council's visit to Athens. 
  Mikhailidhis accused Turkish Cypriot Leader Rauf Denktas of 
delaying tactics on the Cyprus issue and added that, with his 
stance, Denktas is trying to cause confusion in an attempt to 
avoid finally being blamed for the failure to implement the 
confidence-building measures. The foreign minister repeated 
that the Greek Cypriot side accepts the 21 March document as the 
final text, and warned that our side will not participate in any 
discussion to change it. 
  On the sidelines of the Paris conference, the foreign 
minister met with British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd and 
U.S. Under Secretary of State Peter Tarnoff, with whom he said 
he had an interesting talk. 
  Foreign Minister Mikhailidhis also announced that Greece and 
Cyprus have finalized a series of demands that will be put forth 
at the European Union summit that will be held on Corfu. These 
demands aim at promoting Cyprus' application to join the 
European Union. Mikhailidhis discussed the whole issue with 
Greek Alternate Foreign Minister Theodhoros Pangalos behind the 
scenes at the Paris conference. Our goal on Corfu, Mikhailidhis 
said, is to take another step toward setting a date for the 
beginning of accession talks. 

</TEXT>

