<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Charge Summoned as More Minority Arrests Protested </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Charge Summoned as More Minority Arrests Protested </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2605124094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2605124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to information received by the Greek 
Foreign Ministry, more Greek minority members are being arrested 
in Delvine. Foreign Ministry spokesman Konstandinos Bikas said 
today that there is information that the Albanian authorities 
are searching for about 14 people. Four of them have already 
been arrested. 
  The Greek Government has addressed a strong warning to 
Albania to respect the Greek minority and described the Albanian 
actions as a more general policy of intimidation against the 
minority with the aim of causing panic and making people flee 
their homes. The Greek Government will use every legal means to 
protect the Greek minority, the Foreign Ministry spokesman 
stressed and described the Albanian Government's actions as 
tactics reminiscent of times condemned by the democratic 
community. 
  Along with representations lodged by the Foreign Ministry 
with both the [U.S.] State Department and the Albanian Foreign 
Ministry, the Greek side has withdrawn its proposal for a 
meeting between Greek and Albanian delegations to prepare a new 
meeting between their foreign ministers. 
  Referring to a State Department appraisal that Greek 
accusations of Albania's policy toward minority members are 
baseless, the Foreign Ministry spokesman said these appraisals 
have already been overshadowed by the new arrests in Delvine. 
  At noon today, Ambassador Khristos Zakharakis, Foreign 
Ministry secretary general, and Yeoryios Angelakis the 
ministry's Balkan Affairs Department director, summoned U.S. 
Charge d'Affaires James Williams to the Foreign Ministry. 
  Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said a short time 
ago that, following the arrest of Greeks in Albania, Foreign 
Minister Karolos Papoulias will have a telephone conversation 
with UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali. It will probably 
take place today. Venizelos reiterated for the last time that 
Greece considers the improvement of Greek-Albanian relations to 
depend on respect for the rights of the Greek minority in 
Albania. The government spokesman stressed that Greece will 
take all the necessary steps with international organizations 
and in the capitals of countries that have anything to do with 
the issue. 

</TEXT>

