<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papoulias on Concerns Regarding Albania, Turkey </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papoulias on Concerns Regarding Albania, Turkey </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3105200994 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1700 GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC3105200994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Greek-Albanian relations are easing up following 
yesterday's statement by Albanian President Sali Berisha and the 
expected initiative of the European Union [EU] troika. 
  Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias today reiterated that 
Greece has never rejected any proposals for a dialogue, but 
noted that, if necessary, it is determined to take very drastic 
measures to deal with the Albanian provocations. Correspondent 
Mirella Kalostipi reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Kalostipi] Foreign Minister Karolos 
Papoulias harshly warned the Albanian Government that Greece has 
the capability to hinder any brutal attacks against the Greek 
minority and stressed that Tirana's credibility will be judged 
according to its behavior on human rights. He suggested that 
the Albanian authorities stay calm and criticized the ease with 
which they make slanderous accusations against Greece. 
  [Papoulias] Tirana must be particularly calm. It is very 
easy to make various slanderous accusations against Greece, but 
these are unacceptable. Of course, the Greek side has made its 
demarches at all the international forums, particularly the 
European Union. I believe the EU will soon undertake an 
initiative in the direction of protecting the Greek minority's 
human rights. 
  [Kalostipi] Answering a question, Papoulias clarified that 
the Greek Government does not intend to deport Albanians who 
live in Greece. However, he called upon the Albanian president 
to consider the financial benefits from the work of thousands of 
illegal Albanian immigrants in Greece. The foreign minister 
implied that control at the Greek-Albanian border will become 
much stricter. Papoulias also stressed that the issue of EU 
financial aid to Albania depends completely on its stance on 
human rights. 
  Referring to the charges against Omonoia Chairman Sotirios 
Kiriazatis and to his interrogation, Papoulias stressed that 
violent charges during supposed interrogations that aim to 
terrorize members of the Greek minority cannot continue. 
  [Papoulias] Once again I must warn Tirana that Greece has 
the 
capability to hinder any brutal attacks against the Greek 
minority. 
  [Kalostipi] The foreign minister expressed concern at the 
recent number of attacks against the Ecumenical Patriarchate in 
Istanbul, but added that Greece is carefully and calmly 
following the events. He said he intends to meet his Turkish 
counterpart, Hikmet Cetin, on the sidelines of the NATO summit 
that will be held in Istanbul in a few days. Papoulias will 
express the Greek Government's dissatisfaction with the 
slanderous campaign against our country, alleging the training 
of Kurdish guerrillas on Greek territory. Papoulias described 
these accusations as unfounded, adding that they hinder 
Greek-Turkish relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

