<H3> <TI>   Comments on Relations With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Relations With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3105123594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 31 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC3105123594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias has left on a 
three-day official visit to Moscow as part of regular 
Greek-Russian political contacts. During his visit in the 
Russian capital, the Greek foreign minister will meet with his 
Russian counterpart, Andrey Kozyrev, and discuss the improvement 
of bilateral trade and economic relations, the Bosnian crisis, 
and the Balkan situation. 
  Shortly before his departure from the eastern terminal of 
Ellinikon Airport, the foreign minister told correspondents: I 
can only stress once again the importance of this visit. Our 
relations with Russia are excellent. I believe that we have 
quite a few questions on bilateral relations to discuss in a 
positive context and promote them. Mr. Papoulias added: I 
refer to natural gas and the oil pipeline. If we reach an 
agreement on these, and I am certain that we will, they will be 
two important projects for Greece's economy as well as for 
Greek-Russian economic relations. 
  The foreign minister added: Of course, Russia is playing a 
pioneer role in the peace process for the former Yugoslavia. 
Many of our own positions are similar to those of Russian 
foreign policy. I believe that we will hold detailed discussions 
and that we will probably undertake joint initiatives, such as 
convening again the five-member conference between the United 
States, Russia, France, Great Britain, and the European Union's 
troika, which was held in Geneva on 13 May. 

</TEXT>

