<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-105 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Contacts With Leaders `Intensified' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Contacts With Leaders `Intensified' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2705145994 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 26 May 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM2705145994 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Adnan Husayn: "Ankara Ignores Iranian Proposal </F>
for Joint Operation. Turkish Officials Make Arrangements for 
Meeting With Iraqi Kurdish Leaders"] 
  [Text] London -- Iran appears to have failed to convince 
Turkey of the possibility of a joint operation inside the Iraqi 
Kurdish areas which have, over the past three weeks, witnessed 
an armed conflict between the two largest parties there. 
According to identical reports from the Kurdistan Democratic 
Party [KDP] led by Mas'ud Barzani and the Patriotic Union of 
Kurdistan [PUK] led by Jalal Talabani, Turkish Government 
officials have intensified their contacts with the two Kurdish 
leaders to help them bridge their views and end the estrangement 
resulting from the recent fighting between them. 
  Sources have told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that the Turkish 
officials are making arrangements for a tripartite meeting in 
Turkey to be attended by representatives of the Turkish 
Government and the two Kurdish parties, and probably by PUK 
Secretary General Jalal Talabani who is now in Damascus. 
  The Turkish sources said that the discussions at the meeting 
would not be confined to the tension between Barzani and 
Talabani but would also cover relations between Ankara and the 
Kurdish administration in northern Iraq and the situation 
resulting from the exodus of thousands of Turkish Kurds to Iraqi 
Kurdistan to escape the military operations carried out by the 
Turkish Army in the Kurdish areas adjacent to the border with 
Iraq against fighters of the outlawed Workers Party of Kurdistan 
[PKK]. 
  The sources expected the meeting to be held after the 'Id 
al-Adha holiday. The Turkish press reported last week that a 
visiting Iranian delegation had suggested to Ankara that a joint 
operation be launched to put an end to the fighting in Iraqi 
Kurdistan. 
  According to PUK sources, Iranian Revolutionary Guard 
elements are taking part in the operations against PUK forces in 
areas near the border with Iran, and Iranian artillery is 
shelling Iraqi Kurdish areas from across the border. Other 
Kurdish forces and international relief officials have confirmed 
these reports but KDP sources have not. 
  Iran has accused Talabani's party of providing shelter and 
aid for the Kurdish parties opposed to the Iranian Government. 
  Turkey feels that instability in northern Iraq suits the 
PKK, 
which has been fighting the Turkish state for 10 years, in that 
it enables the PKK to set up bases and staging posts in the 
mountainous areas near the border with Turkey. 
  It is worth noting that Turkish President Suleyman Demirel 
announced at a press conference last Monday [23 May] that Turkey 
intended to contact Barzani and Talabani "to promote a peaceful 
solution between them." 
  As regards the armed conflict between the parties of Barzani 
and Talabani, sources of the two parties in the areas where the 
clashes started early this month say that the situation there 
ranges from guarded calm to limited clashes in isolated spots. 
The sources are cautious when it comes to the question of 
whether or not the current truce would develop into a firm peace. 
  Sources have told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that earlier this week 
Barzani and Talabani spoke to each other by telephone, for the 
first time in several days, and, the sources say, they also 
exchanged fax messages focusing on the cease-fire agreements 
reached by their two parties and "emphasizing the importance of 
Talabani's presence in Kurdistan alongside Barzani to implement 
these agreements." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-42267 </DOCNO>
