<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Iceland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Left-Wing Alliance Wins Local Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Left-Wing Alliance Wins Local Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0106115694 Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 30 May 
94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> PM0106115694 </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>
<F P=105>  Danish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Left-Wing Parties Won in Iceland"] </F>
  [Text] The conservative Independence Party and the Social 
Democratic Party, which together form the government of Iceland, 
were the big losers in Saturday's [28 May] local elections. The 
Independence Party lost its empire in Reykjavik, where the party 
has more or less reigned supreme for 64 years. The winners are 
the joint list of left-wing parties which won 53 percent of the 
vote and had eight representatives elected. The Independence 
Party won 47 percent of the vote and had seven representatives 
elected. 
  Ingibjorg Solrun Gisladottir (Women's Alliance), who won a 
great personal victory and is now Reykjavik's new mayor, said 
the result shows that the voters in the capital have grown tired 
of the one-party rule by the Independence Party and want changes 
that place the individual in center stage. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

