<F P=100> CANADA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister: Trade With China Not Linked to Human Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister: Trade With China Not Linked to Human Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106152594 Montreal Radio Canada International in English 
1330 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Montreal Radio Canada International </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Canada will not link its future trade relations with 
China to the issue of human rights. Canada's minister of 
foreign affairs, Andre Ouellet, presented the government's 
policy on China in a speech in Ottawa. 
  He said linking trade and human rights would be 
counterproductive and unlikely to succeed with such a large 
nation as China. He says, however, that Canada won't ignore the 
benefits of increased trade with China. Mr. Ouellet said 
Canada's prosperity as a small nation depends on trade with 
China, but he says Canada will press Chinese leaders in private 
meetings on its human rights behavior. 
  Canada's Prime Minister Jean Chretien met yesterday in 
Ottawa 
with (Wu Bangguo), a member of the Chinese Communist Party's 
Politburo. Mr. Ouellet said meetings such as this will be used 
to discuss China's human rights performance and democratic 
reform. 
  Mr. Ouellet's comments followed accusations from Amnesty 
International. The human rights group said the Canadian 
Government is neglecting its commitment to human rights. The 
criticism comes almost five years after the massacre of 
democracy supporters in Beijing's Tiananmen Square. Amnesty 
says the situation in China hasn't improved since then. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

