<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi, Bossi Locked in `Fresh Duel' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Berlusconi, Bossi Locked in `Fresh Duel' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106185294 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 1745 
GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Italian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The ruling coalition is not only divided in the 
Senate; it is also being lacerated by a fresh duel between 
Umberto Bossi and Silvio Berlusconi. The outcome of this 
personal battle is far from certain. Rocco Tolfa reports: 
  [Tolfa] Allies and antagonists, Bossi and Berlusconi are 
united in the government, but Bossi and Berlusconi are also the 
eternal duellists. Their relationship has always been stormy 
and now it is becoming increasingly bitter in the run-up to the 
European elections. 
  Umberto Bossi says that Berlusconi is the restorer of the 
old 
regime and the leader of an opportunist political movement which 
Bossi compares to an empty box. Bossi has also fired a warning 
shot at Berlusconi: We will not defend the government at all 
costs. 
  Berlusconi is losing patience and says that those who 
believe 
in what Bossi says don't know anything. However, he refuses to 
be more critical because he says that he does not want to create 
tensions in his government and because he is convinced that 
Bossi's outbursts will lose the Northern League votes. 
  The prime minister then passes a pitiless comment: 
Gianfranco Fini is an ally on whim one can depend. 

</TEXT>

