<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Spokesman Calls UN Report `Objective' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Spokesman Calls UN Report `Objective' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0106125394 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0106125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Government Spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis said a 
short while ago that the description of events included in the 
UN secretary general's report is being judged as very objective. 
He stressed that for the first time the UN secretary general is 
clearly blaming the Turkish Cypriot side. Kasoulidhis also 
stressed that indirectly the report blames Turkey as it notes 
that the lack of political will is also found outside Cyprus. 
The main conclusion of the report, the spokesman said, is that 
for the first time it blames the Turkish side for its lack of 
political will and suggests the study of alternative ways to 
promote a solution to the Cyprus issue. 
  Kasoulidhis added that when the report was released, 
President Glavkos Kliridhis repeated that he would be committed 
to accepting the 21 March document if the other side would do 
the same. Kasoulidhis stressed, however, that it is now time 
for alternative ways to be tried to promote the substance of the 
Cyprus issue. 
  The government spokesman announced that the National Council 
will be convened at 0900 on Friday [3 June] morning to discuss 
our position. 

</TEXT>

