<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi Lauds `Warm' Relations With U.S.; Reactions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Berlusconi Lauds `Warm' Relations With U.S.; Reactions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0306091294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2205 GMT 2 
Jun 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0306091294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "`Warm Relations' Between Clinton, </F>
Berlusconi; Fini Satisfied"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, June 2 -- Visiting U.S. President Bill 
Clinton developed a "warm human relationship" with Italian 
Premier Silvio Berlusconi on the first day of his two-day visit 
here, Berlusconi told the press on Thursday evening [2 June]. 
  "Everything went well," Berlusconi told the press after a 
dinner in Clinton's honour this evening. "We have created a 
warm human relationship with Clinton and his wife." 
  Equally pleased at this evening's function was Gianfranco 
Fini, secretary of the National Alliance, who said that there 
was no echo of foreign press concern over the presence of his 
party in the governing coalition. National Alliance was born 
out of the Italian Social Movement, the political heir to the 
Fascist Party. 
  According to Fini, Clinton shook hands with the National 
Alliance leader and showed no reserve at all, "not even in the 
words he spoke when Berlusconi introduced me to him. Of course 
he knew perfectly well who all the people present were, and he 
was cordial with them all in exactly the same way." 
  "To me, Clinton seemed perfectly at ease," Fini added. "If I 
had to say in a word what did not emerge either this evening or 
this afternoon on the Capitoline, I would say it was 
embarrassment. There was everything but embarrassment." 
  Interior Minister Roberto Maroni, who replaced Northern 
League leader Umberto Bossi at tonight's dinner, explained 
Bossi's absence saying that the party chief had an appointment 
with his supporters which took precedence over a formal 
engagement. 
  Also present this evening was Left Democrat Party Secretary 
Achille Occhetto who said "I am happy to have met Clinton, who 
is one of the most dynamic and human politicians around. He is 
a brave man." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

