<H3> <TI>   IAEA `Can No Longer Guarantee' Nonmilitary Use of Uranium </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA `Can No Longer Guarantee' Nonmilitary Use of Uranium </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0206193994 Paris AFP in English 1921 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0206193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rome, June 2 (AFP) -- The International Atomic 
Energy Agency has told UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali 
it can no longer guarantee that North Korea has not used uranium 
for military purposes, a senior U.S. official said here Thursday 
[2 June]. 
  An IAEA report to that effect, delivered to Butrus-Ghali 
Thursday, is also being distributed to the 15 members of the 
Security Council, he said. 
  Earlier the official said that as soon as the IAEA report 
was 
published the United States would ask the UN Security Council to 
impose sanctions against North Korea. 

</TEXT>

