<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Seeks Japanese Cooperation on Energy, Environment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Seeks Japanese Cooperation on Energy, Environment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0306052994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0518 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0306052994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, June 3 KYODO -- The European Union (EU) 
seeks cooperation with Japan in dealing with energy and 
environmental issues, according to the EU's vice president in 
charge of science and technology attending next week's joint 
forum in Tokyo. 
  Antonio Ruberti said Thursday [2 June] he looked forward to 
Japan-EU comprehensive cooperation socially and economically to 
deal with a number of issues, including global warming and the 
reduction of carbon dioxide emissions into the atmosphere. He 
indicated he would also take up the issue of Japan-EU 
cooperation in ensuring the safety of nuclear energy when he 
confers with Japanese Government officials in Tokyo. Ruberti is 
scheduled to arrive in Tokyo on Tuesday for the forum on 
cooperation on science and research that was established last 
October on the basis of a joint declaration in 1991 by Japan and 
the European Community, as the EU was then called. 
  Among the Japanese scheduled to attend the forum opening 
Wednesday are Mikio Omi, director general of the Science and 
Technology Agency, Education Minister Ryoko Akamatsu and leaders 
of the Federation of Economic Organizations (Keidanren). 

</TEXT>

