<H3> <TI>   Shipyard Cited in Taiwan Military Scandal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shipyard Cited in Taiwan Military Scandal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0206132294 Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD in Dutch 2 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BR0206132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Wilton Named in Taiwan Scandal"] </F>
  [Text] The Schiedam shipyard company, Wilton Fijenoord, has 
been named in a major defense scandal in Taiwan involving a 
large section of senior naval officers. 
  A top-ranking member of the military was sentenced to life 
imprisonment this week. The 37-year-old Lieutenant Colonel Liao 
Chih-wei apparently revealed military secrets to the agent of a 
Netherlands company. In the CHINA TIMES, this company was 
identified by civil servants of the Taiwan Defense Ministry by 
the initials "W.F." Seven other officers have been charged, 
together with 10 arms dealers. Chuang Ming-yao, the commander 
of the Taiwan Navy, was forced to resign in April because of the 
affair. 
  Director T. Jonker of the Schiedam shipyard company stated 
that it was all "a complete mystery" to him. Jonker: "We have 
not built any frigates since the 1970's, and we have never 
supplied Taiwan with any frigates. In 1987 and 1988 Wilton did, 
however, supply Taiwan with two submarines." Jonker also said 
that the shipyard company has no agent in Taiwan, but 
representatives often travel between the two countries to 
maintain contacts. 

</TEXT>

