<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry: No More Nuclear Arms Targeted at Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry: No More Nuclear Arms Targeted at Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206153694 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1620 GMT 2 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0206153694 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Sarah Womack, PRESS ASSOCIATION correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Britain has stopped targeting Russia with nuclear 
missiles, the Ministry of Defense announced today. The move is 
in line with an agreement signed by the prime minister and 
President Boris Yeltsin in the Kremlin last February 15 which 
involved a thousand Russian missiles and about 160 British 
weapons. The United States and Russia also stopped targeting 
each this week. 
  An MoD [Ministry of Defense] spokesman said the computers 
which guide British weapons "no longer routinely hold targeting 
information." The weapons were detargeted on May 30. Targets 
which were "held in readiness for insertion into the missiles" 
will be points in the open ocean, he added. 
  The MoD described the move as a "positive demonstration of 
the developing cooperative relationship between the United 
Kingdom and the Russian Federation." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

